item.title: As U.S. Ramps Up Reopening, Restrictions Return in South Korea
item.description: U.S. cities and states progressed with plans to restart their economies, but South Korea reimposed some social-distancing measures around the capital after its biggest daily rise since early April and India reported more than 6,000 new cases for the seventh day in a row.

item.title: China Votes to Override Hong Kong's Autonomy on National Security
item.description: China’s legislature approved a resolution to impose national-security laws on Hong Kong in a bid to crush anti-Beijing protests that have challenged Chinese leader Xi Jinping.

item.title: Chinese Policy Makers Have Stimulus Measures Ready, Premier Says
item.description: Premier Li Keqiang emphasized that China’s abandonment of its formal growth target didn’t diminish the importance of economic growth.

item.title: Most Countries Fail to Capture Extent of Covid-19 Deaths
item.description: A growing pool of global death statistics indicates that few countries are accurately capturing fatalities from the new coronavirus—and in some the shortfall is significant.

item.title: Mexico's Leader Has Answer for All His Needs: The Army
item.description: President Andrés Manuel López Obrador has given his nation’s military a growing role in public works, fighting the coronavirus and confronting drug cartels, in a concentration of power some see as risky.

item.title: U.S. to Stop Allowing Foreign Companies to Facilitate Iran's Civil Nuclear Program
item.description: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said the U.S. would stop allowing foreign companies to facilitate Iran’s civil nuclear activities, a core provision of the 2015 international nuclear agreement.
